{The Schlechter Variation is one of the most resilient and underexplored systems against 1.d4. First tested at the highest level in the 1910 World Championship match between Carl Schlechter and Emanuel Lasker, this line has stood the test of time as a model of classical solidity and hidden depth. While modern theory often gravitates toward sharp lines and computer-preferred continuations, the Schlechter offers a refreshingly human approach—prioritizing structure, flexibility, and long-term strategic plans. This course is a follow-up to "The Fort Knox According to Jobava", and continues our journey in the “Legendary Openings Series According to Jobava”. Once again, we dive into an underrated gem—practical, strategically rich, and ideal for players who want to outprepare their opponents not with brute force, but with timeless chess understanding.} 1. d4 ({In general, you can use the Schlechter against many openings, just as an example:} 1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 {[%csl Bg6]} 5. d4 Bg7 {and we have transposed into the main position.}) 1... d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 ({or} 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nf3 Bg7) 3... Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 {This is the starting position of the Schlechter Defense.} 6. Be2 {[%csl Be2] This is White's big mainline.} ({In the second part of this database we will focus on White's sidelines, on top of everything} 6. Bd3 {which is already not great for White because of} c5 $1 {[%csl Bc5] A move that has been used only once, but it is extremely strong.}) 6... O-O 7. O-O {Usually, in an opening course, the chapters are divided based on the opponent's choices. But this time, it's different—because it's Black who decides! Throughout my career, I've experimented with several different setups in this position, and in this course, I want to share all of them with you. We'll begin by analyzing 11 classical games I’ve played against elite Grandmasters, which will help you understand the practical foundations of each variation. After that, we'll dive into the theoretical section, where I’ll reveal a number of powerful and original ideas in each of these lines. Most importantly, you'll learn how to choose the right variation based on the specific tournament situation.} Bg4 {[%csl Cg4] is Black's most solid line, and I have used it against Anish Giri.} (7... dxc4 {[%csl Cc4] This is a highly professional line. If you study it carefully, even the strongest Grandmasters will struggle to pose you any serious problems. It’s the kind of system you choose when your goal is to neutralize White's initiative and achieve concrete equality from the very start.}) (7... Nbd7 $5 {I have to admit—I really love this move. To be fully honest with you, it does have some small objective drawbacks. But based on my experience, it’s playable, and I’ll share with you all my ideas and practical insights.}) (7... b6 $5 {[%csl Bb6] Practical choice. You can use this one when you feel that you have more experience than your opponent.}) ({There are also other rare lines like} 7... Na6 {[%csl Ca6] a move that I personally like, but it's also risky to play.}) (7... Ne4 $5 {[%csl Be4] Very rare but sound. I have used it myself in the 2024 Olympiad. This is good if you want to play something fresh.}) (7... Z0 {In general, the Schlechter is a strategically excellent opening, and the only reason it’s not commonly played today is fashion. I’ve always believed that once Black fully understands the key ideas, it becomes a practical weapon you can rely on consistently. It’s incredibly flexible and can be used against a wide range of White’s move orders. In practical terms, studying the Schlechter allows you to replace 4 or 5 other systems in your repertoire with a single, universal solution. If you enjoyed the Fort Knox, you’ll love the Schlechter. Same spirit, new territory—solid, surprising, and Jobava-approved.}) *

