1. d4 {t} d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O Bg4 {[%csl Cg4] This is Black's most solid option.} 8. cxd5 $1 {The most critical move, in my opinion.} (8. Ne5 $6 {t} Bxe2 9. Qxe2 Ne4 $1 $132 {White should already try to simplify.}) (8. b3 {t} Ne4 $5 {[%csl Be4] The easiest.} 9. Bb2 (9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Nd2 Bxe2 11. Qxe2 f5 {[%cal Gc6c5] We are ready for c5.} 12. Ba3 {[%cal Rc6c5]} (12. Bb2 c5 $1 $132) 12... Nd7 {[%cal Gc6c5] c5 is once again a threat.} 13. b4 Rf7 $5 $132 {[%csl Bf7][%cal Ra3f8,Ge7e5] I like to remove the rook from Ba3 fire. e7-e5 next maybe, and it's a great game for Black.}) 9... e6 $5 {We can wait an extra move before capturing on c3.} 10. Nxe4 (10. h3 {t} Bxf3 11. Bxf3 f5 $132 {[%csl Gd7,Ge4][%cal Gb8d7] Typical position where Black has excellent play for the two bishops.}) 10... dxe4 11. Nd2 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 f5 {[%cal Gc6c5] with the idea c5.} 13. b4 {logical move against c5, and now:} Nd7 {[%cal Ge6e5] preparing e5.} 14. c5 {[%cal Gd2c4] White is ready for Nc4.} b5 $1 $11 {[%csl Cb5,Cc6,Ce6] Strong positional move after which Black immediately solves all the problems.}) (8. h3 {t White wants to get the pair of bishops, but our last move 7...Bg4 indicates that we were ready to give it.} Bxf3 9. Bxf3 dxc4 $5 {interesting option.} (9... e6 $132 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gf8e8] A solid alternative. Black can proceed with Nbd7 and Re8, and the question of whether White’s two bishops truly make a difference in this position has been debated for over 100 years. In my opinion, it simply leads to a balanced and playable game.}) 10. b3 $1 {White's most testing way.} (10. a4 {t} e5 $1 $146 11. dxe5 Nfd7 12. e6 fxe6 $132 {[%cal Gd7e5,Ge5d3] Ne5-Nd3 next, and it's equal for the engine, but probably OTB easier to play for Black.}) (10. Qe2 {t White's most common continuation.} e5 $1 {[%csl Be5] key break.} (10... Nbd7 {most common move, but after:} 11. Rd1 $1 $14 {[%cal Re7e5] Black won't be in time to push e5.}) 11. Qxc4 (11. dxe5 $6 {t Easy move to play, but it's already a mistake.} Nfd7 12. e6 Ne5 13. exf7+ Rxf7 $15 {also the engine prefers Black.}) 11... Nbd7 (11... exd4 {at} 12. exd4 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7b6] Nb6 next and this is also fine.} 13. Rd1 Nb6 14. Qb3 Qd7 $11 {[%cal Gb6d5] Nbd5 next as in Arutinian-Murzin, 2024.}) 12. Rd1 (12. Qb3 {t} Qb6 $11) 12... Qe7 {[%cal Gf8d8] Rfd8 next.} 13. Qb3 {White's most common and natural try, and here I like:} e4 $1 14. Be2 b5 $1 $146 {with a new interesting position, evaluated "0.00" by the engine. A critical line could be:} 15. d5 Nc5 16. Qc2 b4 $13) 10... cxb3 11. Qxb3 Qb6 12. Rb1 Rc8 $1 $146 {[%csl Bc8] A great novelty that changes the evaluation of this variation.} ({In the recent game Gumularz-Murzin, Black opted for:} 12... Re8 $6 {but now White has the chance to achieve an advantage with:} 13. Qc2 $1 Qc7 14. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5] e5 is a serious positional threat.} e5 {necessary move.} 15. dxe5 Nfd7 16. e6 $1 fxe6 17. Nb5 $16 {Qe5 only move, then Bb2 and White is at least with some initiative, but probably objectively better.}) 13. Qc2 {This was White's best against 12...Re8.} (13. Qxb6 axb6 14. Rxb6 Ra7 $11 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gb7b5] This engame is equal. Black will continue with Nbd7, followed by b5 and eventually e6, then something like Ne8-Nd6. Black is too solid.}) 13... Qc7 14. e4 Nbd7 $1 15. e5 Nd5 $1 {[%csl Bc8] This is why the rook is useful on c8.} 16. Nxd5 (16. Ne4 c5 $13) 16... cxd5 17. Qxc7 Rxc7 18. Bxd5 Nb6 $11 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gb6d5,Ga8c8] e6 next, and Black has excellent pieces that more than compensate for White's bishops pair. This endgame is just equal.}) (8. Qb3 {t A less accurate move order for White if compared to 8.cxd5.} Qb6 $1 {[%csl Bb6] This move is not possible for Black in the 8.cxd5 cxd5 9.Qb3 move order.} 9. cxd5 (9. Qxb6 {t} axb6 10. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 11. Nxd5 cxd5 {the doubled 'b' pawns mean zero here, for example:} 12. Bd2 Nc6 13. Rfc1 e5 14. dxe5 Nxe5 $11 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Gg7b2]}) 9... Qxb3 $1 10. axb3 cxd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gb8c6] We want to just play Nc6.} (10... Nxd5 {looks normal, but maybe here White can play something long like:} 11. Bd2 $14 {[%cal Gh2h3] h3 next, objectively equal but it could be slightly unpleasant for Black over the board.}) 11. b4 {[%cal Gb4b5] White tries to justify his doubled 'b' pawns.} Nbd7 $11 {[%cal Gf8c8,Gd7b6] Rfc8-Nb6, with an equal endgame.}) 8... cxd5 (8... Nxd5 $6 {[%csl Rg4] not in the spirit of the 7...Bg4 line.} 9. Qb3 $16) 9. Qb3 {White's best chance, and it's also how Giri played against me.} (9. h3 $6 {t is too slow.} Bxf3 $1 {[%csl Gf3] The point of the line.} 10. Bxf3 Nc6 $132 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gd8d7,Gf8c8] Black has no issues.} 11. Qb3 {White is not even in time to create problems with Qb3 because of} Na5 $1 $11 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Ga8c8,Ge7e6] then Black can play with a6-b5-Rc8-e6...}) 9... b6 {Black's positional idea is very simple: to take on f3 and play e6, and later trade everything on the c-file and make a draw.} (9... Bc8 $14 {The second line of engine, but not so pleasant to play.}) (9... Qb6 $2 {not possible now because of} 10. Nxd5 $16) 10. h3 {The best try.} (10. Bd2 {can be met with:} Ne4 $1 {[%csl Be4][%cal Yd2e1,Ge7e6]} 11. Be1 Nc6 12. h3 {Carlsen-Artemiev, 2020.} Nxc3 13. Bxc3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 e6 $11 {[%cal Gd8d7,Gf8c8] Qd7-Rfc8 next, and White's two bishops mean zero here.}) 10... Bxf3 11. Bxf3 e6 12. Bd2 {Most common try.} (12. Qa4 $5 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Ga4d7,Yd8d7] t} a6 $1 {[%csl Ba6] The engine recommendation.} 13. Bd2 Nbd7 $11 {[%cal Gd8b8,Ga8a7,Gf8c8] And slowly the evaluation starts to drop, Qb8-Ra7-Rc8 is a cool defensive plan.}) 12... Qd7 $5 {[%csl Bd7][%cal Gf8c8,Gd7b7] Rc8, then maybe Qb7 and it's equal.} (12... Nc6 {is how Black usually plays, but I think Qd7-Rc8 is the priority.}) 13. Be2 $5 {[%csl Be2][%cal Ge2a6] Alexey Dreev wanted his Be2 to work on the queenside.} (13. Rfc1 Rc8 {[%cal Gb8c6] Difficult to suggest a plan for White. The most logical move is:} 14. Be2 {and it transposes to the game Dreev-Perun, 2000.}) 13... Rc8 14. Rfc1 Qb7 $1 $146 {[%cal Ga7a6,Yb7b6] defending b6 and preparing a6.} (14... Bf8 15. a4 $14 {White had some pressure in Dreev-Perun, 2000.}) 15. a4 a6 $11 {[%csl Ga6][%cal Gb8c6,Gg7f8] whenever White pushes a5, Black will have b5. Only now we will continue with the typical moves Nc6-Bf8, and White doesn't have a single idea to create problems.} *

