1. d4 {t} d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O dxc4 {[%csl Bc4] This is Black's most concrete option. The idea is to reach equality in a "forced" way, without giving White any chance to achieve a game.} 8. Bxc4 Bg4 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge7e5] Black's main idea will be Nbd7-e5, and for this reason, very often we are ready to give up our bishop on f3.} 9. Be2 {White's second idea.} (9. h3 {is White's mainline and we will analyze it in the next chapter.}) 9... Bxf3 $1 {This is a more precise move order, in my opinion.} (9... Nbd7 {This is almost an automatic move for Black, but now White can try:} 10. e4 Bxf3 11. gxf3 $1 $14 {[%csl Bf3][%cal Ge7e6,Gd8c7,Gf6h5] Objectively slightly better for White, although the position is practically complicated (we can play Qc7-Nh5-e6...) .} (11. Bxf3 e5 {transposes to the main position that we will analyze via the more accurate 9...Bxf3 move order.})) 10. Bxf3 (10. gxf3 {t makes little sense now because of:} Qc7 11. e4 Rd8 $1 {[%csl Bd8][%cal Ge7e5] e5 is a serious threat, so White has to commit to f4 or e5, and this makes the position very interesting to play for us.} 12. f4 (12. e5 Nd5 $13) 12... e6 $132 {[%cal Gc6c5]}) 10... Nbd7 {[%cal Ge7e5] We are now ready for e5.} 11. e4 {White's most logical move, of course.} e5 12. dxe5 $5 {Positional option.} (12. Be3 $6 {t} exd4 13. Bxd4 Re8 $36 {[%cal Gd7e5,Gd8e7,Gd7c5] The engine already slightly prefers Black.}) (12. d5 {t} cxd5 13. exd5 (13. Nxd5 {t} Nc5 14. Bg5 Ne6 $132 {[%csl Ge6,Rf3] White has two bishops, but I honestly prefer our knight on e6 in this structure.}) 13... Re8 {This is an interesting position, but White also runs some risk.} 14. Bg5 (14. d6 $5 $146 {t engine's move, but it looks strange:} Re6 15. Bxb7 Rb8 16. Ba6 Nc5 {s} 17. Qe2 Rxd6 18. Bc4 Ne6 {[%cal Ge6d4]} 19. Bxe6 Rxe6 20. Be3 Qe7 $11) 14... h6 15. Be3 e4 16. Be2 Rc8 $1 {s} (16... Nb6 $6 {Aronian-Yu, 2019.} 17. d6 $1 $14) 17. Qd2 h5 18. Rad1 a6 $13 {[%cal Gg7f8,Gf8d6] Bf8 next, and it's a complicated position for three results, evaluated "0.00" by the engine.}) 12... Nxe5 13. Be2 Re8 $1 {[%csl Be8] Only move for the equality.} (13... Qe7 $6 {Most common move, but inaccurate.} 14. f4 $1 Rad8 15. Qc2 Ned7 16. Rb1 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4]}) 14. f4 {compared to the 13...Qe7 line, here we can go for:} (14. Be3 {t} b5 $5 $13 {[%cal Gb5b4,Ye5c4] with b4 or somewhere even Nc4 ideas.}) (14. Kh1 $5 {t engine's prophylactic move.} Ned7 $5 {[%csl Bd7][%cal Rf2f4] Black can also play a prophylactic move against f4.} 15. f3 Qe7 $132 {[%csl Bg7][%cal Ga8d8] Rd8 next. It's a fight. White has two bishops, but Black has great pieces, and Bg7 is very strong. Keep in mind that if White develops with Be3, then Nd5 is often an idea.}) 14... Qb6+ 15. Kh1 Rad8 {[%csl Rd1][%cal Ge5g4] after White's queen moves, we will have Neg4 ideas.} 16. Qc2 Neg4 17. Bf3 Ne3 18. Bxe3 Qxe3 19. e5 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gc5e6] Nc5 (or Nf8) - Ne6 next.} *

