1. d4 {t} d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O dxc4 {[%csl Bc4] This is Black's most concrete option. The idea is to reach equality in a "forced" way, without giving White any chance to achieve a game.} 8. Bxc4 Bg4 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge7e5] Black's main idea will be Nbd7-e5, and for this reason, very often we are ready to give up our bishop on f3.} 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nbd7 {[%csl Bg7][%cal Ge7e5] Black is ready to push e5. In general, we are not worried about White's pair of bishops because once we will push e5, our Bg7 will be extremely strong.} 11. Rd1 {[%csl Bd1][%cal Bd1d8,Ye7e5] the most logical move. White's rook goes on the 'd' file, anticipating Black's e7-e5 idea.} (11. e4 {t logical move, but Black is fine thanks to:} Nb6 $1 {[%csl Gb6,Rc4,Rd4][%cal Gb6c4,Gd8d4] with the double threat Qxd4 and Nxc4.} 12. Qd3 Nxc4 13. Qxc4 b5 {the most concrete way.} ({I believe that Black's position is fine also after a move like:} 13... a5 $5) 14. Qxc6 Qxd4 15. Be3 (15. Qxb5 $6 {t} Nxe4 $15 {[%csl Rc1,Gg7] Bg7 stronger than Bc1.}) 15... Qc4 {[%csl Cc4] professional move.} 16. Qxc4 bxc4 $11 {[%cal Gf8b8,Gf6e8] Rfb8-Ne8 next, and it will end in a draw very soon.}) 11... e5 $1 {[%csl Be5] This is a very important concrete move. Without it, Black would be much worse.} 12. d5 {the most logical move.} (12. dxe5 {t} Nxe5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge5f3] winning a tempo against White's Qe2.} 13. Qe2 Qe7 14. Bb3 Rfd8 $132 {[%csl Bg7] This position is a perfect example of the fact that Black shouldn't be worried about White's pair of bishops, because Bg7 is very good.}) (12. Bb3 {t harmless move.} Qe7 13. Bd2 (13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Qe2 {trans in 12.dxe5.}) 13... Rad8 14. a3 $5 {just useful move, but now Black can force equality with:} (14. Be1 {t} exd4 15. exd4 Nb6 $132 {[%cal Gb6d5] Nbd5 next.}) 14... c5 $11 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Rf3b7,Gd8b8] not the only move, but a good one. Qxb7 impossible because Rb8 and Bb3 will be hanging.}) (12. a4 $5 {t rare move, but the engine likes it.} exd4 13. exd4 Nb6 14. Bb3 Nbd5 {For the engine this is +0,15, so almost full equality, but still some little pressure for White. With precise moves we will solve everything, for example:} 15. a5 (15. Bg5 {t} h6 16. Bd2 Qd7 $11) 15... Qd7 16. a6 Rfe8 {[%csl Be8] s no need to be afraid of axb7.} 17. g4 $5 {concrete try.} (17. axb7 Qxb7 $11 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gb7b2] Black has good counterplay on the 'b' file.}) 17... h6 18. h4 b5 19. g5 hxg5 20. hxg5 Nxc3 21. bxc3 Nd5 $13 {[%csl Rg1] if White continues to overpush, he will also be under risk.}) 12... e4 $1 {[%csl Be4] extremely important move: without it, Black is much worse.} 13. Nxe4 {Principled continuation.} (13. Qe2 {t} cxd5 14. Nxd5 Ne5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge5c4,Ge5d3] we will take on c4, or play for Nd3 if White retreats the bishop.} 15. Nc3 (15. Nxf6+ {t} Qxf6 16. Bd5 Qf5 $1 $15 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5,Gg7][%cal Ge5d3] s White is already worse. One game ended in this funny way:} 17. Qc2 Rad8 18. Bxb7 Nf3+ $1 {[%csl Bf3]} 19. gxf3 (19. Kh1 Ng5 $19 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Gg5h3] Nxh3 ideas.}) 19... exf3 $19) 15... Qe7 $132 {[%csl Be5,Bf6,Bg7] all Black's pieces are great.}) (13. Qf4 {[%cal Rd7e5] t Compared to 13.Qe2, this move prevents Ne5.} cxd5 14. Nxd5 Nb6 15. Nc3 (15. Nxf6+ {t risky for White.} Qxf6 16. Qxe4 (16. Qxf6 Bxf6 17. Bb3 Rfc8 $36 {[%cal Gb6c4] Nc4 next.}) 16... Rfe8 {s} 17. Qg4 h5 18. Qe2 Nxc4 19. Qxc4 Rad8 $36 {[%csl Ra1,Rc1,Bf6,Bg7] Thanks to the activity of the pieces, Black has more than compensation.}) 15... Qe7 16. Bb3 Rac8 $11 {[%cal Gb6c4] Nc4 next, and Black was fine in Raja - Neuman, 2025.}) 13... Nxe4 {Most of the players prefer this way.} (13... Ne5 $5 {at Chinese variation. It is very forced:} 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Qe2 Nxc4 16. Qxc4 cxd5 17. Rxd5 Qc8 $44 {[%csl Bc8,Bf6] s Black has full compensation for the sacrificed pawn, and it will be a draw very soon. Maybe for somebody it's not pleasant to play without a pawn, but here it's really impossible for White to finish the development without giving back something.} 18. Qb3 Qe6 {[%csl Be6]} (18... Rd8 $5 {also fine.}) 19. Bd2 {Bai-Li Chao, 2025.} Rfd8 $1 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 21. Bc3 Bxc3 22. Qxc3 h5 $11 {[%cal Gd8d1] Black controls the 'd' file, and White's extra pawn means nothing objectively.}) 14. Qxe4 Nb6 15. Bb3 {The mainline.} (15. Qc2 {t was tried sometimes, but Black is very active after:} cxd5 16. Be2 Qh4 $132 {[%csl Cb6,Cg7,Bh4][%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8]}) (15. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b3] t White's second most common try. The idea is to prepare b3, but Black is in time to concretely equalize:} Re8 16. Qd3 Nxc4 17. Qxc4 Re5 $1 {[%csl Ge5] key move.} 18. e4 (18. d6 {t} Re6 19. d7 Qc7 $11 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Ga8d8,Ge6e7] d7 will fall very soon.}) 18... Qe8 $1 {[%csl Be8] s Second key move. In most of the games, White just accepts the simplifications with:} 19. Be3 (19. f3 {white wants to keep the pawn at all costs, but this is not really a winning try:} cxd5 20. Rxd5 Rxd5 21. Qxd5 Rd8 22. Qb3 Qe6 $44 {[%csl Rb1,Rc1,Bd8,Bg7] draw because Black's pieces are very active.}) 19... Rxe4 20. Qb3 cxd5 21. Rxd5 b6 $11) 15... cxd5 16. Bxd5 (16. Qb4 {t strange move as it allows:} a5 $1 $132 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ga5a4]}) (16. Qd3 {t} Qe7 $132 {[%csl Bg7][%cal Ga8c8,Gf8d8] s Rac8-Rfd8 next. Nothing to worry about, thanks to the strong Bg7. Let's follow a recent game:} 17. Rb1 Rac8 18. Qb5 Rc5 19. Qb4 Rfc8 20. Bd2 Nc4 21. Bxc4 dxc4 $11 {Girel - Neuman, 2025.}) (16. Qf3 {t} Qf6 $1 17. Qxf6 Bxf6 18. Rb1 {most natural move, and now a logical continuation could be:} (18. Bxd5 {is not really a winning attempt.} Nxd5 19. Rxd5 Rfd8 $11 {[%csl Ra1,Rc1,Bf6]}) 18... Rfd8 {s} 19. Bd2 Nc4 20. Bc3 Bxc3 21. bxc3 b5 $11 {[%csl Cc4] with an equal endgame.}) 16... Nxd5 17. Rxd5 (17. Qxd5 {t} Qxd5 18. Rxd5 Rfd8 $44 {[%csl Bd8,Bg7] White doesn't have any winning chance because Black is too active.}) 17... Qb6 {[%csl Bb6,Bg7] There are around 40 games here where White tries to finish the development and slowly use the extra pawn, but it's only about practical tries, objectively Black has full compensation.} 18. Qd3 {[%cal Ge3e4] most common try, with the idea e4.} (18. Rb1 {t} Rad8 19. Rd2 Qa6 $1 (19... Qa5 $6 20. b4 $14 {[%csl Ra5,Bb4] with tempo against Qa5, as in Vorobiov-Neuman, 2018.}) 20. a4 (20. b4 $6 Rxd2 21. Bxd2 Qxa2 $15 {[%csl Ba7,Bg7]}) 20... Qa5 $11 {[%cal Rb2b4,Ga5a4] against b4, now Black has Qxa4.}) 18... Rad8 {Black's most common continuation.} 19. e4 Bd4 $1 {[%csl Bd4] White has a lot of moves, but objectively it's always equal, for example:} 20. Kh1 {The most famous try.} (20. Be3 {t} Bxe3 21. Qxe3 (21. fxe3 Qxb2 $11) 21... Qxe3 22. fxe3 Rde8 $11 {[%csl Re3,Re4] easy to understand that it's a draw.}) (20. Qf3 {t} Rxd5 (20... Rfe8 $6 {Sonis-Divrnyy, 2017.} 21. Bh6 $1 $14 {[%csl Bh6]}) 21. exd5 Qf6 $11 {[%cal Gf8d8] Rd8 next with easy equality.}) 20... Bxf2 21. Bh6 Rxd5 (21... Rfe8 {is also fine.}) 22. exd5 Rd8 23. Rd1 Qd6 24. Qc3 f6 25. Rf1 Bh4 26. Qb3 {Bareev-Kramnik, 1994.} Rd7 $1 {The easiest move. Black has no reason to fear something.} (26... Bg5 $2 {Kramnik's move, but now White has a winning advantage.} 27. Bxg5 fxg5 28. Qxb7 Qxd5 29. Qxa7 $18 {Bareev-Kramnik, 1994.}) {White can play some moves, but with 1-2 accurate answers from Black, it will be a draw.} 27. Qc4 (27. Qa4 Bg5 28. Bxg5 fxg5 29. Qxa7 Qxd5 $11) 27... Bg5 28. Bxg5 fxg5 29. Qc8+ Kg7 $11 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Rc8f8] no mate. The 7...dxc4 line is a variation that objectively solves all the problems for Black. It's not so common like other openings because sometimes Black has to remember a few precise moves, but if you study it well, and I believe this file will give you a great knowledge, it could be a very realiable life-time variation, where not even a very well-prepared Grand Master will be able to pose you any problem.} *

