1. d4 {t} d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 {[%csl Od7] According to statistics, this is Black's second most common move. I have also used it in some games, but I believe that, objectively, it's a bit dubious.} 8. cxd5 $1 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Yb8c6] Using the committed position of Nd7.} (8. b3 {t} Ne4 $1 {[%csl Be4]} 9. Bb2 {and now Black has a cool move} (9. Nxe4 {t always better to check it.} dxe4 10. Nd2 f5 {[%cal Gc6c5]} 11. Bb2 a5 $1 $132 {[%cal Rb3b4,Ge7e5,Gc6c5] better to prevent b4, and then c5 or e5 next.} (11... c5 12. b4 $1 {strong engine's resource.} cxb4 13. Qb3 a5 14. a3 $14)) 9... e5 $1 {it was used by Gledura in 2018.} 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qa5 ({or} 12... Qg5 $5 {at} 13. Qc2 Bxe5 14. Bxe5 Qxe5 $11 {[%cal Gc8f5]}) 13. Qc2 Bxe5 $11 {Gledura-Galyas, 2018. Black even managed to win the game.}) (8. b4 {t has been tried by a lot of strong players, but it's premature:} dxc4 $1 9. Bxc4 Nb6 (9... b5 $132 {[%cal Ga7a5] at with a5 next could be another good way for Black.}) 10. Bb3 (10. Bd3 {t} Nfd5 $36) 10... Nbd5 11. Nxd5 cxd5 $11 {[%cal Gc8f5] Bf5 next.}) (8. Qc2 {[%csl Yc2] t} Nb6 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gc8f5] I like this move. We free the Bf5 idea, which would make feel Qc2 uncomfortable.} (8... Re8 $5 {[%cal Ge7e5] at preparing e5.} 9. Rd1 e5 $5 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Rxe5 12. cxd5 cxd5 $11 {[%cal Gc8f5] Bf5 next.}) 9. cxd5 (9. b3 {t} Bf5 10. Qd1 (10. Bd3 $6 {t} Bxd3 11. Qxd3 dxc4 12. bxc4 c5 $15) 10... Ne4 $132 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gh7h5] Black is fine. Next move could be a5 or h5.}) (9. c5 {t} Nbd7 $1 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge7e5] Re8-e5 next, with a Chebanenko-style structure.} 10. b4 {let's follow the game Feller-Iordachescu, 2011.} Re8 11. Bb2 e5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Rxe5 14. Nb5 Re7 {s} 15. Nd6 (15. Nd4 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Gf6e4] Ne4 next.}) 15... Ne8 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qc3+ Kg8 18. Nxc8 Rxc8 $36 {the engine already prefers Black.}) 9... Bf5 {[%csl Rc2,Gf5]} 10. Qb3 Nfxd5 $132 {[%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4] maybe a5-a4 next.}) (8. Qb3 {t} e6 $132 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gb7b6] b6 next, and Qb3 looks misplaced.}) 8... Nxd5 {Taking with the knight is objectively dubious, but it has always been my choice. The point is that I wanted to have an unbalanced game.} (8... cxd5 {Objectively better, but extremely sad.} 9. a4 $1 {[%csl Ba4][%cal Rd7b6,Ga4a5] unpleasant position for Black, cause the knight belongs on c6.} Re8 {[%cal Ge7e5] preparing e5.} (9... a5 $6 {White won't play Qb3 anymore.} 10. b3 $1 $16 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gc1a3,Yb8c6] White has a clear advantage, the knight on d7 is left with no home.}) 10. Qb3 e6 $14 {[%cal Gd7b8,Gb8c6] White's position is slightly more pleasant, but I see that the engine often continues with Nb8-Nc6, and claims that Black is more or less fine.}) 9. e4 $1 {[%csl Be4] Only move for White to fight for an advantage.} (9. Nxd5 $6 {t White's most common continuation.} cxd5 {[%cal Ge7e5] Basically e5 next with equality.} 10. Qb3 {[%csl Ob3][%cal Yd7b6,Yd7f6] Against e5, but Qb3 is not always well placed.} (10. Bd2 $6 {t} e5 $1 $11 {[%csl Ge5] I was fine in my game against Maurizzi.}) 10... Nf6 11. Bd2 Ne4 12. Bb4 Bg4 {[%cal Ge4g5] s with the idea Ng5.} 13. h3 (13. Rfc1 Ng5 $11) 13... Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Qd7 15. Rfc1 a5 16. Be1 a4 17. Qd3 Nf6 $11 {[%cal Gf8c8,Gg7f8,Ge7e6] Rfc8-e6-Bf8. Here the two bishops are not so relevant.}) 9... Nc7 $5 {[%csl Bc7] This is how I liked to play it. Nc7 offers chances for an interesting game, although objectively Black is worse here.} (9... Nxc3 {is Black's best.} 10. bxc3 {[%cal Yc6c5] Black won't go for c5 anymore, but after:} e5 $14 {White keeps the advantage with solid moves, but Black can also more or less play it.}) 10. Be3 {[%csl Ge3] Engine likes to put the bishop here immediately.} Nb6 11. a4 $1 $146 {[%csl Ba4][%cal Ra7a5,Gd1b3] This was probably the best, since I can't really stop it with a5.} (11. h3 {t Useful, but it allowed my usual plan:} f5 {[%csl Bf5] White objectively can fight for an advantage also here, but Black at least gets some practical chances.}) 11... Be6 {s} (11... a5 12. Qb3 $18 {[%csl Rb6] big problems with Nb6.}) 12. b3 $16 {[%csl Rb6] To stop Nc4 and White has a clear advantage. CONCLUSIONS: You can play 7...Nbd7 and then recapture on d5 with the pawn, where the position is very solid for Black, although slightly worse from a human sense (for the engine it remains equal) . If you want to play it in my stye, then you can take on d5 with the knight, but you should be aware of the fact that the engine doesn't fully approve it.} *

