1. d4 {t} d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O Ne4 $5 {I used this move once.} (7... Na6 {I have used this move in many blitz games, but I cannot recommend it because of:} 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Qb3 $14 {[%csl Ra6] where probably Black's best is Nb8. If you remember, in my game against Gledura I have played Nc7, but that was not great.}) (7... a6 {it's a playbale move, but it's more in the Chebanenko spirit than in the Schlechter, that's why I have never used it.}) (7... Be6 $5 {Banusz move. It's approved by the engine, but I have never liked it because of:} 8. cxd5 (8. Ng5 Bf5 9. Qb3 Qb6 $11) (8. b3 Ne4 9. Bb2 Nxc3 10. Bxc3 Bg4 $11 {[%cal Ge7e6]}) 8... cxd5 9. Qb3 Qb6 {I didn't find anything better, but this is quite sad.} (9... b6 10. Bd2 $14 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gf1c1] Rfc1 next, and Be6 is misplaced.}) 10. Qxb6 axb6 11. Bd2 $14 {/=. White can play a long and risk-free endgame.}) (7... Bf5 {I am not a big fan of this move.} 8. Qb3 (8. h3 $5 $14 {[%csl Yf5,Gh3] h3 could be more useful than Bf5.}) 8... b6 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Ne5 $14) 8. Re1 $5 {[%csl Be1] Engine's move.} (8. Qb3 {t Most common move, but Black has many good ideas:} dxc4 $1 {[%csl Rb3,Bc4] The easiest.} 9. Qxc4 (9. Bxc4 {t} Nd6 $11 {[%cal Gc8f5] With equal chances.}) 9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 b6 11. Qb3 c5 $132 {[%cal Gb8c6] Black can go for a Hybrid Gruenfeld system, with natural counterplay.}) (8. Nxe4 {t is not great immediately.} dxe4 9. Nd2 {can be met with:} (9. Ng5 $6 {t} f5 $36 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Ge7e6,Yg5h3] The knight is misplaced.}) 9... c5 $1 {[%csl Bc5] Key idea.} (9... f5 $6 {Not this, since it allows White to gain space with b4.} 10. b4 $14 {[%csl Gb4,Gc4,Gd4] With a nice queenside control.}) 10. dxc5 f5 $44 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Gg7a1] Black has excellent compensation.}) (8. h3 {[%csl Gh3] t White replied with a useful move.} Nxc3 $1 {This was the most precise.} (8... b6 $6 {Starting with b6 was not precise.} 9. Nxe4 $1 {White can capture now.} dxe4 10. Nd2 f5 11. b4 {[%csl Gb4] And we reach an unpleasant position for Black.} c5 {can be met with:} 12. bxc5 bxc5 13. Nb3 $1 cxd4 14. Nxd4 $36 {[%cal Rb8c6,Gd4c6] The position is a bit dangerous for Black.}) 9. bxc3 b6 $11 {[%cal Gc8a6] Black slowly solves all problems.}) 8... Bf5 $5 {we can change plan.} ({The idea of Re1 can be seen in the following variation:} 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 b6 10. Ba3 Ba6 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. e4 $1 dxe4 13. Bxa6 Nxa6 14. Rxe4 $14 {[%csl Be4]}) 9. Qb3 Qd7 {Black is very solid, for example:} 10. cxd5 Nxc3 11. bxc3 cxd5 12. c4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6a5]} 14. Bd2 {many moves are possible.} Rab8 $132 {[%cal Gb7b5] somewhere b5 could be an idea.} (14... e6 $5) 15. a4 e6 $132 {[%csl Be6][%cal Gf5e4] the engine likes this e6 move. Then Black very often continues with Be4. It's a 0.20 position, playable for both sides.} *

