1. d4 {t} d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Bd3 {[%csl Cd3] For many years, this move was considered as important as 6.Be2.} c5 $1 {[%csl Cc5] A revolutionary idea discovered by the Swedish IM Trost Edvin.} ({After the inclusion of:} 6... O-O 7. O-O c5 $6 {this move doesn't work so well.} 8. dxc5 dxc4 9. Bxc4 Qxd1 {White can now comfortably recapture with the rook.} 10. Rxd1 $16 {[%csl Bd1]}) {There is only one game in this position, so the theory has not been developed yet.} 7. O-O {GM Suleymanli's choice, and the engine also goes for it.} (7. dxc5 {t} dxc4 8. Qa4+ (8. Bxc4 {t} Qxd1+ {The point is that White doesn't have a comfortable recapture.} 9. Nxd1 (9. Kxd1 {t} Nbd7 $132 {[%cal Gd7c5] already -0,10 evaluation.}) 9... Ne4 $1 $132 {[%cal Ge4c5,Rb2b3,Yb8d7,Yd7c5] Nxc5 next, and b3 is not allowed. -0,12 evaluation.} (9... Nbd7 10. b3 $5 Nxc5 11. Ba3 $132 {is White's idea.})) 8... Nbd7 9. Bxc4 O-O {[%cal Gd7c5] Black is ready for Nxc5.} 10. Qa3 {[%csl Ba3][%cal Ba3c5] logical move: White tries to keep the pawn, but without committing for the b4 move.} (10. O-O {t} Nxc5 $132 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] b6-Bb7 next and Black is already slighlty preferable (-0,15) .}) (10. b4 {t concrete move.} Ne4 11. Nxe4 Bxa1 {White has full compensation for the exchange, but no more than that. For example:} 12. O-O Ne5 {[%csl Be5] Precise move.} 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 $13) 10... Qc7 11. b4 (11. O-O {t} Nxc5 $132 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] b6-Bb7 next.}) 11... Ne5 $1 {[%csl Be5] Most precise move.} (11... Ne4 $2 {would be a mistake now, because of:} 12. Nd5 $16 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc1b2] Bb2 next.}) (11... a5 {t also fine.} 12. Nb5 Qb8 13. Bb2 axb4 14. Qxb4 Ne4 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 $11 {[%cal Gd7c5] Fedoseev-Peng, 2019.}) 12. Be2 (12. Nxe5 {t} Qxe5 13. Bb2 Qg5 $1 $44 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gc8h3] Bf1 only move for White.}) 12... Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 Bg4 $1 {[%csl Bg4] Clear equalizer:} 14. Bxg4 Nxg4 15. h3 Ne5 16. O-O a5 $11 {[%csl Rc5,Ge5][%cal Ga5b4,Gg7a1,Ge5d3,Ge5c4] White can't hold on to the pawn.}) (7. cxd5 {t} Nxd5 {I see here two main tries for White:} 8. Nxd5 (8. Qb3 {t positional try that invites a structural change.} Nxc3 9. bxc3 Nc6 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Gd8c7] Black is ready to continue with b6-Bb7-Qc7, and Qb3 is not well placed.} (9... O-O {less precise because of:} 10. Ba3 $1 cxd4 11. cxd4 $14 {[%cal Rd8a5,Ga3b4] if Qa5+ White has Bb4.}) 10. O-O (10. Ba3 cxd4 11. cxd4 Qa5+ $13 {[%csl Bc6,Re1][%cal Ra3b4] no comfortable way to defend from check.}) 10... O-O 11. Rd1 Qc7 $132 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Ya8c8,Yf8d8] b6-Bb7 next, then rooks in the center and easy play for Black.}) 8... Qxd5 {[%cal Gc5d4] Black is ready for cxd4, that's why White should try:} 9. e4 {[%cal Gd4d5] which supports d5 next.} Qd7 {Best place for the queen.} (9... Qd6 {I prefer Qd7 because here White can try:} 10. d5 e6 11. Bc4 $14 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Rb7b5] White is slightly better.}) 10. d5 e6 $1 (10... O-O $6 {inaccurate move order.} 11. Be3 b6 12. Qd2 e6 13. Bh6 $14) 11. O-O (11. Bc4 $6 {t} b5 $1 $15 {[%csl Bd7] that's why Qd7.}) 11... exd5 12. exd5 O-O 13. Qb3 Qd6 $11 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7e5] Nd7-Ne5 next.}) 7... cxd4 8. exd4 (8. Nxd4 {t very harmless.} O-O $36 {[%csl Bg7] Black can only be preferable with the strong Bg7.}) 8... Nc6 {We are playing a good version of the Panov structure from the Caro-Kann (basically we have avoided the concrete cxd5-Bc4-Qb3 lines) .} 9. cxd5 (9. h3 {[%cal Rc8g4] t} O-O (9... dxc4 {t} 10. Bxc4 O-O $132 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gc6e7,Yb7b6,Yc8b7,Cc8d7] is one way. we have transposed into a position with some games, but Black's easy plan is usually e6-Ne7 and then or b6-Bb7 or Bd7-Bc6.}) 10. c5 {typical move in Panov spirit, and now Black is fine with two options:} b6 {[%csl Bb6] more professional approach.} (10... Bf5 {t} 11. Bxf5 gxf5 $132 {[%cal Gf6e4] Ne4 next. The engine gives a very small plus for White (+0,30) but it's an interesting fight.}) 11. cxb6 Qxb6 12. Na4 {[%cal Ga4c5] White's only idea is to play for the c5 square, but it's equal after:} Qb8 13. Be3 {[%cal Ga1c1]} e5 $1 {Good reaction.} 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 $11 {[%cal Gc8f5] s Bf5 next.} 16. Rc1 Bf5 17. Bxf5 Qxf5 $11 {[%cal Gf6e4] Easy moves next.}) 9... Nxd5 10. Be4 {[%csl Bd5] Suleymanly concretely plays for the d5 square.} Be6 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gh7h6] Black wants h6 next and fully secure the position.} 11. Ng5 {Last chance for White to create something.} Nxc3 (11... O-O $5 $146 {at was also good according to the engine.} 12. Nxe6 fxe6 $132 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8d7,Ga8d8] The pawn structure looks strange, but Qd7-Rad8 next, and Black's pieces are all very active.}) 12. bxc3 Bc4 13. Re1 O-O $132 {Black got a good position in Suleymanli-Trost, 2025, and even managed to win the game later.} *

