1. d4 {t} d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. cxd5 {White aims for an Exchange Slav.} (6. Qb3 {[%csl Yb3] t} O-O 7. Bd2 {Most common.} (7. cxd5 {t Bad understanding.} cxd5 $132 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gb8c6,Gc6a5] Qb3 just misplaced (Nc6-Na5 ideas) .}) (7. Bd3 {t} dxc4 $1 8. Bxc4 b5 9. Be2 (9. Bd3 {t} Nbd7 10. O-O e5 $36 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Rd4e5,Gd7c5] using the hanging position of Bd3.}) 9... a5 $1 {[%csl Ba5] prophylactic move against a4 (if a4, b4!) .} (9... Bf5 $2 10. a4 $16 {[%cal Rb5b4]}) 10. O-O (10. a4 $2 {t} b4 $17 {[%csl Ga5]}) 10... Bf5 $1 {[%cal Rb3c2] against Qc2.} (10... a4 $6 11. Qc2 $14) 11. Bd2 Qd6 $36 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge7e5] Nbd7 and probably e5 next. The engine already prefers Black.}) (7. Be2 {t} dxc4 8. Qxc4 $5 {Mendonca-Khoroshev, 2025. Here for Black I like the concrete solution:} b5 9. Qd3 (9. Qb3 a5 {trans in 7.Bd3.}) 9... b4 10. Ne4 Ba6 11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. Qc2 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 c5 $11 {[%csl Bc5] It can be more pleasant for Black.}) 7... e6 {[%csl Cd5,Be6][%cal Gb7b6,Gf6e4] logical move. The idea is to continue with b6 and play later (or Ne4) .} (7... Qb6 {is how the recent game Abdusattorov-Nepo, 2024 continued, but I don't like Qb6 move at all.}) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Rf6e4] logical against Ne4, and now Black has a strong plan:} (8. Rc1 {t} Ne4 $36 {[%csl Be4] Some initiative.}) (8. Be2 {t} Ne4 $132 {[%csl Be4]}) 8... b6 9. O-O c5 $1 $146 {[%csl Bc5] better to play it now and develop Bc8 only later. Black is immediately fine, for example:} 10. dxc5 bxc5 11. Rfd1 (11. cxd5 $6 exd5 $36 {[%csl Rb3,Rd3] Qb3 and Bd3 misplaced.}) 11... Nbd7 12. Rac1 Ba6 $132 {[%cal Ga8b8] Black is absolutely fine.}) 6... cxd5 {[%csl Rc1,Rg7] Exchange Slav when Black's bishop is on g7 and it's not great (no influence on the queenside) , but also White's bishop is on c1 and not on f4.} (6... Nxd5 7. Be2 $14 {[%csl Rc6] Gruenfeld when Black plays c6 instead of c5. Of course, White didn't adopt the most ambitious set-up, that's why it's only slightly better for White.}) 7. Bb5+ {Concrete try.} (7. Be2 {t} O-O 8. O-O Nc6 $132 {[%cal Gf6e4,Bc8g4] Probably Ne4 next, or just Bg4.}) (7. Bd3 {t} O-O 8. O-O Bg4 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nc6 $132 {[%cal Ge7e5] Equal position. At some point Black can even push e5 to open Bg7.}) 7... Bd7 8. Qb3 e6 $5 {[%csl Yd5,Be6][%cal Ye6d5] the simplest: we just defend d5.} (8... Bxb5 $2 {Very common mistake. In fact, this is Black's most common move.} 9. Qxb5+ Qd7 10. Ne5 Qxb5 11. Nxb5 Na6 12. Ke2 $16 {[%csl Ra6] Very unpleasant endgame for Black.}) 9. Bxd7+ (9. Ne5 {t} Bxb5 (9... O-O $5 {t also good if you don't want to sacrifice a pawn.} 10. Nxd7 Nfxd7 $132 {[%cal Gb8c6] Nc6 next and the two bishops are not important here.}) 10. Qxb5+ Nbd7 11. Qxb7 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. f4 O-O 14. O-O f6 $44 {Full compensation for sure.}) 9... Qxd7 10. Ne5 Qc7 $1 {Important move, to support Nc6.} (10... Qe7 $2 11. Qb5+ $16 {Georgiev-Piskov, 2024.}) 11. Qa3 {[%cal Re8g8] White uses his last shots to prevent 00.} (11. Qb5+ {t} Nc6 $11 {[%csl Bc6,Cc7] The point.}) (11. O-O {t} O-O $11 {[%cal Gb8c6] Nc6 next.}) 11... Bf8 12. Qa4+ Nc6 13. Bd2 Be7 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8] 00 next and Black is absolutely fine.} *

