1. d4 {t} d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. b3 {White gives priority to the development of Bc1.} (6. b4 {[%csl Ob4] t} O-O 7. Bb2 {Black has a lot of good continuations} Bg4 {simple and good.} (7... a5 $5 {t} 8. b5 a4 $1 {[%csl Ba4]} 9. Nxa4 {critical.} Qa5+ 10. Nc3 Bg4 $36 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gf6e4,Gc6b5] with great compensation.}) 8. h3 (8. Qb3 {t} a5 9. b5 {Tomashevsky-Mamedyarov, 2006.} a4 $1 $146 10. Nxa4 Qa5+ 11. Nc3 Nbd7 $17 {[%cal Ge7e5] s} 12. Be2 dxc4 13. Qxc4 Nb6 14. Qd3 (14. Qb3 Be6 15. Qc2 cxb5 16. O-O Rfc8 $19) 14... Na4 15. Qd2 Nxb2 16. Qxb2 cxb5 17. O-O b4 $17 {[%csl Bb4]}) 8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Qd6 $5 {[%cal Gd6b4] nice provocative move. Engine's top choice.} 10. c5 (10. a3 {t} a5 $132) 10... Qc7 $36 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge7e5] Nbd7 - e5 next, and Black is quicker.}) (6. Bd2 {[%cal Ga1c1] t old plan, White gives priority to Rc1.} O-O 7. Rc1 Ne4 $5 {[%csl Be4] the simplest.} 8. cxd5 (8. Be2 {t} Nxd2 9. Qxd2 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nd7 $132 {[%csl Cc8,Cg7][%cal Ge7e5] e5 next and I would take Black because of the two bishops.}) 8... Nxd2 9. Qxd2 (9. Nxd2 {t} cxd5 10. Qb3 {Efimov-Borisek, 2007. Black had the chance to overtake the initiative with:} e5 $1 11. dxe5 d4 12. exd4 Nc6 $36) 9... cxd5 10. Be2 (10. h4 {t} h5 $132 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gb8c6] Bg4-Nc6 next.}) 10... Nc6 11. O-O Bg4 $11 {No problems at all.}) (6. Qc2 $6 {[%csl Rc2] t Strange move because Qc2 will be often misplaced, just remember this idea:} O-O 7. Bd3 c5 $1 $44 {[%csl Rc2] all the complications will for sure work well for Black.}) (6. h3 {[%cal Rc8g4] t White's priority is to prevent Bg4, but it costs an important tempo.} O-O 7. Be2 dxc4 {The most principled.} (7... b6 {[%csl Yh3][%cal Gc8b7] is also a good plan here, because h3 is not so useful against this.}) 8. Bxc4 b5 9. Bd3 (9. Be2 {t} Nbd7 $1 {[%csl Bd7][%cal Ga7a6,Gc6c5] no need to spend time for Bb7: we can continue with a fast Nbd7-a6-c5.} 10. O-O a6 {[%cal Gc6c5]} 11. e4 (11. b4 {[%csl Ob4] t when White commits for b4, we can change plan.} e5 $132 {[%csl Ce5]}) 11... b4 {[%csl Re4]} 12. Na4 Nxe4 $132) 9... Bb7 ({Black's immediate plan} 9... Nbd7 10. O-O a6 {[%cal Gc6c5] with the idea c5, fails here due to} 11. e4 $1 $16 b4 12. Na4 $16 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Rf6e4] And compared to the 9.Be2 variaiton, White's bishop on d3 makes here a big difference.}) 10. O-O Nbd7 11. a3 (11. e4 $6 {t} c5 $1 $36 {[%csl Re4] Typical reaction:} 12. e5 Bxf3 $1 13. Qxf3 Nh5 $15 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc5d4,Gd7e5] Black is better.}) 11... a5 $132 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gc6c5] b4 next followed by c5.}) 6... O-O 7. Bb2 {and here Black could go for the typical break} c5 $1 {[%csl Bc5] Good way to handle the position.} 8. dxc5 $146 {Engine's continuation.} (8. Nxd5 {t} Nxd5 9. cxd5 cxd4 $5 (9... Qxd5 {t simple for equality.} 10. Bc4 Qd8 $11) 10. Bxd4 Qxd5 11. Bxg7 Qa5+ 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Nxd2 Kxg7 $11 {[%csl Rc3] Objectively equal, but I would take Black because somewhere in the future the c3 square could become an issue.}) (8. Be2 {t} Nc6 9. O-O cxd4 10. Nxd4 (10. exd4 {t} Bg4 $132 {Black gets a fantastic version of the Panov variation.}) 10... Nxd4 11. exd4 (11. Qxd4 $2 {t tactical mistake.} Ne4 12. Qd3 Bf5 $19 {[%csl Bd3] White loses material.}) 11... b6 $132 {[%cal Gc8b7] easier to play for Black.}) 8... Ne4 9. Rc1 dxc4 $1 {[%csl Bc4] important move.} 10. Qxd8 (10. Bxc4 $4 {t} Bxc3+ 11. Bxc3 Qxd1+ $19 {[%csl Rc3,Rf2][%cal Ge4f2,Ge4c3] Tactical trick.}) 10... Rxd8 11. Bxc4 {better to be accurate now.} Nc6 $1 {[%csl Bc6][%cal Ge4c5] Nxc5 only on the next move.} (11... Nxc5 {gives White some practical chances after} 12. Ba3 $1 Nd3+ (12... Bxc3+ 13. Rxc3 Ne4 {is met with:} 14. Bxe7 $1 $16 {[%csl Be7][%cal Yd8e8,Gc3d3] Tempo.}) 13. Bxd3 Rxd3 14. Nd5 $1 Nc6 15. Nxe7+ Nxe7 16. Bxe7 Bf5 17. O-O $14 {/= Objectively draw, but White has practical chances.}) 12. Ke2 {[%csl Oe2] To stay with the king in the center.} (12. O-O {t} Nxc5 $11) 12... Nxc5 13. Rhd1 (13. Ba3 {t} Bxc3 14. Rxc3 Ne4 {[%cal Ra3e7] No Bxe7.} 15. Rcc1 a5 $132 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gc6b4,Gc8f5,Ge4c3] Dynamic ideas.}) 13... Be6 14. Bxe6 Nxe6 $11 {[%cal Gg8f8,Gf8e8] Easy equality. If you don't know how to proceed, just play Kf8-Ke8.} *

