1. d4 {t} d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 g6 {Playing the Schlechter against the Classical Slav move order gives White some extra options:} 5. h3 $1 {[%csl Bh3] Very deep move, and the best one in my opinion.} (5. Bf4 {t is not problematic.} dxc4 6. e3 Be6 $13 {Interesting position.}) (5. Bg5 {t} Ne4 $1 $36 {[%csl Ge4] Black is more than fine.}) (5. Qb3 {t} Bg7 {Solid.} (5... dxc4 {at Concrete.} 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qb3 Be6 8. Qc2 b4 9. Na4 Bf5 10. Qc4 Bg7 {s} 11. Qxb4 O-O 12. e3 Nbd7 13. Be2 Nd5 14. Qd2 e5 $1 {[%csl Be5] To activate the pieces.} 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. O-O Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 Re8 $44 {Full compensation.}) 6. cxd5 Nxd5 {I prefer with the knight.} (6... cxd5 {allows:} 7. Bg5 $36 {With some ideas, but also fine for Black.}) 7. e4 Nxc3 8. bxc3 O-O 9. Be2 c5 {[%csl Yb3] The queen on b3 is not fantastic in the Gruenfeld.} 10. Be3 cxd4 11. cxd4 Nc6 12. Rd1 Qb6 $11 {Fine for the engine.}) (5. cxd5 {t Positional answer.} cxd5 6. Bf4 Nc6 {[%cal Gf8a3] The bishop belongs on the f8-a3 diagonal, but it's unclear why Black needs g6 then. However, I still believe Black is fine.} 7. h3 (7. e3 {t} Nh5 8. Be5 (8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 Bg7 $1 $13 {[%cal Gg6g5] g5 only later} (9... g5 $2 10. Ne5 $16)) 8... f6 9. Bg3 e6 $13 {[%cal Gh5g3] Position for 3 results.}) 7... Ne4 $1 {[%csl Be4] only chance to achieve something normal.} (7... Bg7 8. e3 $14 {[%csl Rg7] Bg7 misplaced because no queenside influence.} Ne4 9. Rc1 $1 Nxc3 10. Rxc3 $14) 8. e3 (8. Rc1 {White won't be able to comfortably recapture with the rook on c3.} Nxc3 9. Rxc3 {[%csl Bf8]} e5 $1 $13 {[%cal Gf8b4] looks good and interesting.}) 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bg7 {if you like this position, you can play it.} 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O {[%cal Gc3c4,Ge3e4] White can play c4 or e4 at some point.} Na5 $132 {[%cal Gc8d7,Ga8c8]} (11... b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] at difficult to choose between Na5 and b6.})) 5... Ne4 $5 $146 {Maximum I was able to find, but of course it's not something stable, although it should be objectively playable.} (5... dxc4 6. a4 {[%csl Rg6,Gh3][%cal Ge2e4] h3 much more useful than g6 in the Classical Slav, for example:} Nd5 {new position, maybe playable as a surpirse.} (6... Bf5 7. e3 e6 8. Bxc4 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gg2g4] g4 always a problem.})) (5... Bg7 6. cxd5 $1 {[%csl Gd5] only now cxd5, and White has tricked us to a worse Exchange Slav version.} cxd5 7. Bf4 $14) 6. e3 (6. Bf4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 dxc4 $13 {is one way.}) 6... Bg7 7. Bd3 Bf5 $5 (7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 O-O 9. O-O $14 {[%cal Ge3e4] e4 at some point.}) 8. O-O O-O $5 {for a complicated game.} (8... Nxc3 {t} 9. bxc3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 O-O $14 {/= slightly better for White, but Black is very solid.}) 9. Qc2 (9. Bxe4 {t leads to equality} Bxe4 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Ng5 e5 $11 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Ge5d4] simplifications are coming.}) 9... Na6 $1 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Ga6b4] Engine's line.} 10. a3 Nxc3 11. Bxf5 (11. bxc3 {t} Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Re8 $132 {[%csl Ra3,Ga6] a3-Na6 good inclusion for Black (no Be3 for example, sometimes Nc5 or Nc7 ideas.}) 11... gxf5 12. bxc3 e6 $13 {Complicated new position, for the engine it's + 0,30, but OTB it's probably a 50-50 fight.} *

